name: quadrupole-time-of-flight-mass-spectrometer
notes: FUNCTION: The system generates superior quality mass spectrometry (MS) and tandem mass spectrometry (MS/MS) data from both atmospheric pressure ionization (API) and matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization (MALDI) techniques. DESCRIPTION: The QSTAR  &#174;   XL Hybrid  LC/MS/MS System is a high-performance, hybrid quadrupole time-of-flight mass spectrometer designed for protein identification and characterization and drug metabolism studies. The unique flexibility to switch between the standard API NanoSpray  &#8482;  source and the new oMALDI  &#8482;   2 ion source  makes the QSTAR  &#174;   XL System the preferred  choice for proteomics. Specific scan modes such as precursor ion scanning, enabled by the patented LINAC  &#8482;   Pulsar collision cell  technology, identify the type and location of post-translational modifications or drug metabolites with outstanding specificity and sensitivity. FEATURES: Enhanced ion optics for highest sensitivity and reliability. Excellent mass accuracy and stability yield unequivocal molecular weight and high-quality structural information. Unique, patented LINAC  &#8482;   Pulsar collision cell technology  enables the most sensitive product ion and precursor ion scan capabilities for metabolite, protein and peptide, and post-translational modification determination. Maximum flexibility with a comprehensive selection of interchangeable, application-specific ion sources; new oMALDI  &#8482;   2 source for increased sensitivity.  Sensitive and rugged IonSpray  &#8482;   , TurboIonSpray   &#174;   ,  and atmospheric pressure chemical ionization (APCI) ion sources for routine low-level drug metabolism identification and characterization. New NanoSpray  &#8482;   ion source for capillary liquid  chromatography (LC) provides increased sensitivity and throughput for protein and peptide identification and characterization. New PhotoSpray  &#8482;   source for analysis of low-molecular-  weight, highly polar compounds via atmospheric pressure photoionization. Extended MS and MS/MS mass range (6,000 and 40,000 m/z) expands scope of protein and peptide
